0300-gpu-liverpool/0042-amdgpu-uvd-v4-2-fw-mirror-at-300000000.patch
# 0043: v76d-β-2-A3 — add PTE_WRITEABLE to the UVD GART bindings.
# A2 brought the fw to life. Fault changed to PROTECTIONS=0x10 (write
# permission), which means the fw is now WRITING to its own region but
# our PTEs were read-only. Add WRITEABLE flag.
0300-gpu-liverpool/0043-amdgpu-ps4-uvd-gart-pte-writeable.patch
# 0044: v76d-β-2-A4 — extend fw mirror BO from 1920 KB to 3.1 MB to cover
# all 3 Sony UVD regions (region 1 firmware, region 2 heap/IB, region 3
# msgq). A3 had zero VM faults but VCPU still stalled at STATUS=0x4. If
# the fw silently depends on region 2/3 being mapped (even with zeros),
# this should let it complete bring-up.
0300-gpu-liverpool/0044-amdgpu-uvd-v4-2-extend-mirror-all-3-regions.patch
# 0045: v76d-β-2-A5 — instrument 2-sec STATUS poll. Sample 10 VCPU
# registers at 5 timepoints (t=0, 400, 800, 1200, 1600 ms) during the
# poll and print a compact table after timeout. Pure observability —
# tells us if the VCPU is hung early (all static) or progressing but
# not signaling ready (some values change but bit 1 never sets).
0300-gpu-liverpool/0045-amdgpu-uvd-v4-2-instrument-status-poll.patch
# 0046: v76d-β-2-A6 — line-by-line review found 2 divergences from
# Sony's start_baikal: (1) we call uvd_v4_2_mc_resume which writes 3
# UDEC_ADDR_CONFIG registers Sony NEVER touches (mainline's tile
# config might corrupt Liverpool's UVD decode engine); (2) 0x3bd3/4/5
# clock-enable order was 3-4-5, Sony does 4-5-3. Both fixed.
0300-gpu-liverpool/0046-amdgpu-uvd-v4-2-skip-mc-resume-fix-clock-order.patch
# 0047: v76d-β-2-A7 — write 0x00000001 at region 2[0] (heap) and region
# 3[0] (msgq). A6 showed VCPU alive + cache syncing but STATUS bit 1
# never sets. Hypothesis: fw polls one of these locations for a "host
# ready" signal. If A7 unblocks, narrow down to single location next.
#
# 2026-05-11 22:21 RESULT: ❌ REGRESSION — cache stops reaching 0x3f7f
# synced pattern entirely (stuck at 0x196f). Writing 1 at heap[0] or
# msgq[0] broke fw cache fill. Likely interpretation: those slots are
# SIZE FIELDS, not magic flags. fw read "1 byte" → couldn't allocate
# cache backing → aborted. PATCH DISABLED below; kept in tree for ref.
# 0300-gpu-liverpool/0047-amdgpu-uvd-v4-2-host-ready-magic-region2-3.patch
# 0048: v76d-β-2-A8 — A7c + A9 combined: write region SIZES at region 2[0]
# and region 3[0] (0x124000 and 0x4000) AND change k clock divider 4→1.
# A7 regression proved fw reads those slots; if they're size fields, real
# sizes unblock. AND k=4 might be too slow for VCPU init — try fastest.
0300-gpu-liverpool/0048-amdgpu-uvd-v4-2-region-sizes-and-k1.patch
# 0049: v76d-β-2-A9 — extend STATUS poll 2s → 10s, sample every 1s (10
# samples). If fw needs more startup time on Liverpool, the longer
# wait reveals it. If 10s still fails, rules out "needs more time"
# definitively.
0300-gpu-liverpool/0049-amdgpu-uvd-v4-2-extend-status-poll-10s.patch
# 0050: v76d-β-2-A14+A11 — re-enable mc_resume (skip UDEC writes) +
# change k clock divider 1→15. A14 tests if mc_resume has subtle side
# effects we missed (the UDEC writes were harmful, but other writes
# might matter). A11 with k=15 (slowest) should slow cache cycle ~15x
# if k is a pure clock divider.
0300-gpu-liverpool/0050-amdgpu-uvd-v4-2-a14-mc-resume-noudec-plus-a11-k15.patch
# 0051: v76d-β-2-A15 — write Sony's IOCTL-returned constants (0x300308000
# user-buffer-start, 0x20000 size) at region 2/3[0] instead of A8's plain
# sizes. Replaces 0048's writes with better-grounded magic values that
# Sony's actual userspace observes via IOCTL surface.
0300-gpu-liverpool/0051-amdgpu-uvd-v4-2-a15-sony-ioctl-constants-as-magic.patch
# 0052: v76e-B1 — Sony-style per-vmid 2-level page directory. DISABLED after
# 2026-05-12 hw test: STATUS bit 1 still didn't fire AND the minimal PD broke
# mainline's vmid 15 ring_test (fault at VA 0 → amdgpu probe died with -110).
# Confirmed PD walk shape isn't the gate. Patch kept in tree for reference;
# do not re-enable unless paired with a fix that mirrors flat GART for
# low-VA mainline accesses (would be "B1.1").
# 0300-gpu-liverpool/0052-amdgpu-uvd-v4-2-b1-per-vmid-pd.patch
# 0053: v76e-A17 — skip STATUS-bit-1 deadlock, proceed to ring init even if
# bit 1 didn't fire. Hypothesis: STATUS bit 1 only fires AFTER fw processes
# its first ring packet (Sony's userspace queues immediately, no kernel poll).
# Lets ring_test submit a packet — either fw was ready (success) or we get
# a clear fault signal instead of timeout.
0300-gpu-liverpool/0053-amdgpu-uvd-v4-2-a17-skip-status-poll.patch
# 0054: v76e-A18 — UVD soft-fail. Make uvd_v4_2_hw_init always return 0 even
# on internal failure. After 17 iters, UVD is structurally blocked on SBL/SMU
# access (see orbis-dungeon/rooms/sbl-driver.md). Soft-failing lets amdgpu
# probe complete → DRM/display/Hyprland work; UVD stays non-functional but
# software video decode covers it.
0300-gpu-liverpool/0054-amdgpu-uvd-v4-2-a18-soft-fail-hw-init.patch
# 0055: v76e-A19 — VCE soft-fail (sibling of A18 for UVD). VCE on PS4 hits the
# same SBL/SMU structural blocker. A18 fixed UVD but VCE then kills amdgpu
# probe at -110. Same fix in vce_v2_0_hw_init's ring_test loop.
0300-gpu-liverpool/0055-amdgpu-vce-v2-0-a19-soft-fail-hw-init.patch
# 0059: 2026-05-12 — disable UVD + VCE entirely on Liverpool/Gladius. A18/A19
# soft-failed hw_init but VCPU still ran partial bring-up, leading to runaway
# UVD-VA-0x300000000 fault storm under sustained SBL probing (2.6M faults/5s).
# Skip both engines via early_init -ENODEV. SBL writes can't drive the SAMU
# from our context anyway (see sbl-port/2026-05-12-stealth-auth-confirmed.md).
0300-gpu-liverpool/0059-amdgpu-disable-uvd-vce-entirely-no-samu-auth.patch
# 0056: v76e-B1.1-α — drop the VC1_CNTL.PAGE_TABLE_DEPTH=0 override from 0040.
# A18/A19 soft-fail removed the need for the flat-walk hack; DEPTH=0 was
# silently swallowing amdgpu_vm's per-vmid PT_BASE writes, which is why
# Hyprland's CPF faulted at VA 0x268000 in VMID 1. Restoring mainline
# DEPTH=1 lets amdgpu_vm program per-vmid PDs on every submission.
0300-gpu-liverpool/0056-amdgpu-gmc-v7-0-b11-alpha-revert-depth-override.patch
# 0057: v76e-SBL-P1 — Sony SBL/SAMU mailbox primitives v1. Disabled after
# 2026-05-12 hardware test + Ghidra re-dig revealed the trigger/ack
# offsets are SAMU-INTERNAL register indices (accessed via the
# indirect window at 0x22000/0x22004), not direct byte offsets in
# rmmio. Superseded by 0058. Kept in tree for the result write-up
# but not in the active series.
# 0300-gpu-liverpool/0057-amdgpu-ps4-sbl-phase1-mailbox-primitives.patch
# 0058: v76e-SBL-P1-v2 — split direct (mailbox data regs at
# rmmio + 0x22070..0x2207c) from indirect (trigger + ack via
# rmmio + 0x22000/0x22004 index/data window). This matches Sony's actual
# gc/samu.c access pattern. Re-runs the "does SAMU respond?" probe.
0300-gpu-liverpool/0058-amdgpu-ps4-sbl-phase1-v2-direct-and-indirect-access.patch

